comment: why droping all the empty rows?¶

I have to drop all the empty rows in other not to be bais with the dataframe, if i try to fill it up by calculating the variance, the mean, median, mode.then use the median to fill the whole data, there are lot of them (about 1270 rows), out of 1691 of initial datas that i have. that means have been bias. So therefore, in other to work with the most important rows and without been bias. also in other to get accurate result i have to drop those empty rows

EDA Univariate Analysis¶

Univariate Analysis is use to analyse, describe, or to check for the distribution of only one(uni) dataset, it check how values are distributed in each dataset.

  • I make use of boxplot from seaborn to check for the skewness and outliers in the dataset. (skewness shows the shape or assymmentry of the entire distribution of a data point while Outliers are the extreme individual datapoint)
  • I also make use of Bar plot to check for the distributions in each dataset
In [20]:
# checking for the skiness and outliers in our numeric variable
import seaborn as sns
for col in num_cols:
    print(col)
    print('skew:',round(data[col].skew(),2))
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 4))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    data[col].hist(grid=False)
    plt.ylabel('count')
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.boxplot(x=data[col])
    plt.show()

age
skew: 0.54

amt_weekends
skew: 0.99

amt_weekdays
skew: 1.12

  • all the numerical columns shows a +(Positive)skewness and have outliers(out of range)

             order = data['nationality'].value_counts().index);

             order = data['gross_income'].head().value_counts().index);

ax = sns.countplot(y='type', hue = 'gender', data=data, palette='colorblind', order = data['type'].value_counts().head().index)
total = data['type'].count()
ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0], fmt=lambda x: f'{(x/total)*100:.1f}%')
ax.margins(x=0.1)
ax.set(xlabel='Count', ylabel='type', title='type of tobacco by gender')
ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), fontsize=7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
